{"title_page": "Declaration of St James's Palace", "text_new": "{{Infobox summit meeting\n| name         = First Inter-Allied Meeting\n| other_titles = Declaration of St James's Palace\n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| country      = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| date         = 12 June 1941\n| motto        =\n| venues       =  [[St James's Palace]]\n| cities       =  [[London]]\n| participants = {{flag|United Kingdom}} <br>{{flag|Canada|1921}} <br>{{flag|Australia}} <br>{{flag|New Zealand}} <br>{{flag|Union of South Africa}} <br>{{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgian government in exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Czechoslovakia}} [[Czechoslovak government-in-exile|Provisional Czechoslovak Government]] <br>{{flagicon|Kingdom of Greece}} [[Greek government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Luxembourg}} [[Luxembourg government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Dutch government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Norway}} [[Norwegian government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Poland}} [[Polish government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Kingdom of Yugoslavia}} [[Yugoslav government-in-exile]] <br>{{flag|Free France}}\n| chairperson  = \n| follows      = \n| precedes     = [[Atlantic Charter#Acceptance by Inter-Allied Council and by United Nations|Second Inter-Allied Meeting]]\n| website      = \n| keypoints    = No [[separate peace]] with the [[Axis powers]], commitment to a peace based on \"willing co-operation of free peoples\"\n}}\n\nThe '''Declaration of St James's Palace''' was the first joint statement of goals and principles by the [[Allies of World War II]].<ref name=UN>{{cite web|title=1941: The Declaration of St. James' Palace|url=https://www.un.org/en/sections/history-united-nations-charter/1941-declaration-st-james-palace/index.html|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=15 April 2020|date=2015-08-25}}</ref> The declaration was issued after the first Inter-Allied Meeting, an Allied conference at [[St James's Palace]] in London. It took place on 12 June 1941 between representatives of the [[United Kingdom]], the four co-belligerent British [[Dominion]]s, the [[Free France|Free French]], and eight [[List of governments in exile during World War II|governments in exile of countries under Axis occupation]]. The declaration stated the Allies' commitment to continue the war and established principles to serve as the basis of a future peace.\n\n==Background==\n\nAfter the [[Battle of France]], the exiled governments of Poland, Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg established themselves in London and began to work with the British to coordinate resistance activities and carry on the fight.<ref name=yapou>{{cite web |url=http://governmentsinexile.com/yapouintroduction.html |title= Governments in Exile, 1939-1945: Leadership from London and Resistance at Home |last1=Yapou |first1=Eliezer |date=August 1998 |website=Yapou: Governments in Exile |publisher=Edith Yapou }}</ref> Charles de Gaulle's [[Appeal of 18 June]] likewise signaled the beginning of the [[Free France|Free French]] movement. By 1941, the Czech National Liberation Committee under [[Edvard Bene\u0161]] also won recognition as the [[Czechoslovak government-in-exile|Provisional Czechoslovak Government]] as it cooperated ever closer with Britain.<ref name=yapou/>\n\nThe [[Balkans campaign (World War II)|Balkans campaign]] ended on 1 June 1941, leaving both Greece and Yugoslavia under Axis occupation. Both of their governments went into exile; [[Yugoslav government-in-exile|the government]] of [[Peter II of Yugoslavia]] joined the Western Allied exiles in London, while the [[Greek government-in-exile|Greek government]] of [[George II of Greece|George II]] set up in Cairo.\n\nLondon, as the capital of the only belligerent power in Europe not under Axis occupation, became the center of Allied diplomatic activity.<ref name=yapou/> By June 1941, the city had already been subjected to 22 months of combat in the [[Battle of Britain]] and subsequent [[The Blitz|London Blitz]].<ref name=UN/>\n\n==Content and impact==\nThe Declaration of St James's Palace made three resolutions. In the first, the parties affirmed their alliance, pledging to assist one another in the war against [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] and [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Italy]] and committing \"the utmost of their respective capacities\". The second pledged that the Allies would enter into no [[separate peace]], stating that there could be no peace until the threat of Axis domination was past. The third resolution committed the Allies to the principle of a peace based on the \"willing cooperation of free peoples\" in which \"all may enjoy economic and social security.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://avalon.law.yale.edu/imt/imtjames.asp |title=St. James Agreement; June 12, 1941 |date=2008 |website=[[Avalon Project]] |publisher=[[Yale Law School]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | publication-date =September 1946 | date =June 12, 1941 | year =1941 | title =United Nations Documents, 1941\u20141945 | edition =2nd | place =London | publisher =Royal Institute of International Affairs | page =9 | url =https://archive.org/details/unitednationsdoc031889mbp | accessdate = 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe declaration was the first statement by the Allied Powers expressing a vision for a postwar world order.<ref name=UN/> In August of 1941, Britain and the United States laid out this vision in a more detailed form in the [[Atlantic Charter]]. In September, a second Inter-Allied meeting, which now included [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] ambassador [[Ivan Maisky]], issued a resolution endorsing the Charter. In January 1942 a still larger group of nations issued the [[Declaration by United Nations]], endorsing the same principles initially put forward at St James's and pledging to jointly resist the Axis.<ref name=UN2>{{cite web|title=1942: Declaration of The United Nations|url=https://www.un.org/en/sections/history-united-nations-charter/1942-declaration-united-nations/index.html|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=15 April 2020|date=2015-08-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Allied World War II conferences]]\n* [[German-occupied Europe]]\n{{wikisource|Declaration of St James's Palace}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Diplomatic history of World War II}}\n\n[[Category:World War II conferences]]\n[[Category:1941 in law]]\n[[Category:1941 in international relations]]\n[[Category:1941 conferences]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom in World War II]]\n[[Category:June 1941 events]]\n[[Category:1941 documents]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox summit meeting\n| name         = First Inter-Allied Meeting\n| other_titles = Declaration of St James's Palace\n| image        = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| country      = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| date         = 12 June 1941\n| motto        =\n| venues       =  [[St James's Palace]]\n| cities       =  [[London]]\n| participants = {{flag|United Kingdom}} <br>{{flag|Canada|1921}} <br>{{flag|Australia}} <br>{{flag|New Zealand}} <br>{{flag|Union of South Africa}} <br>{{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgian government in exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Czechoslovakia}} [[Czechoslovak government-in-exile|Provisional Czechoslovak Government]] <br>{{flagicon|Kingdom of Greece}} [[Greek government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Luxembourg}} [[Luxembourg government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Dutch government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Norway}} [[Norwegian government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Poland}} [[Polish government-in-exile]] <br>{{flagicon|Kingdom of Yugoslavia}} [[Yugoslav government-in-exile]] <br>{{flag|Free France}}\n| chairperson  = \n| follows      = \n| precedes     = [[Atlantic Charter#Acceptance by Inter-Allied Council and by United Nations|Second Inter-Allied Meeting]]\n| website      = \n| keypoints    = No [[separate peace]] with the [[Axis powers]], commitment to a peace based on \"willing co-operation of free peoples\"\n}}\n\nThe '''Declaration of St James's Palace''' was the first joint statement of goals and principles by the [[Allies of World War II]].<ref name=UN>{{cite web|title=1941: The Declaration of St. James' Palace|url=https://www.un.org/en/sections/history-united-nations-charter/1941-declaration-st-james-palace/index.html|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=15 April 2020|date=2015-08-25}}</ref> The declaration was issued after the first Inter-Allied Meeting, an Allied conference at [[St James's Palace]] in London. It took place on 12 June 1941 between representatives of the [[United Kingdom]], the four co-belligerent British [[Dominion]]s, the [[Free France|Free French]], and eight [[List of governments in exile during World War II|governments in exile of countries under Axis occupation]]. The declaration stated the Allies' commitment to continue the war and established principles to serve as the basis of a future peace.\n\n==Background==\n\nAfter the [[Battle of France]], the exiled governments of Poland, Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg established themselves in London and began to work with the British to coordinate resistance activities and carry on the fight.<ref name=yapou>{{cite web |url=http://governmentsinexile.com/yapouintroduction.html |title= Governments in Exile, 1939-1945: Leadership from London and Resistance at Home |last1=Yapou |first1=Eliezer |date=August 1998 |website=Yapou: Governments in Exile |publisher=Edith Yapou }}</ref> Charles de Gaulle's [[Appeal of 18 June]] likewise signaled the beginning of the [[Free France|Free French]] movement. By 1941, the Czech National Liberation Committee under [[Edvard Bene\u0161]] also won recognition as the [[Czechoslovak government-in-exile|Provisional Czechoslovak Government]] as it cooperated ever closer with Britain.<ref name=yapou/>\n\nThe [[Balkans campaign (World War II)|Balkans campaign]] ended on 1 June 1941, leaving both Greece and Yugoslavia under Axis occupation. Both of their governments went into exile; [[Yugoslav government-in-exile|the government]] of [[Peter II of Yugoslavia]] joined the Western Allied exiles in London, while the [[Greek government-in-exile|Greek government]] of [[George II of Greece|George II]] set up in Cairo.\n\nLondon, as the capital of the only belligerent power in Europe not under Axis occupation, became the center of Allied diplomatic activity.<ref name=yapou/> By June 1941, the city had already been subjected to 22 months of combat in the [[Battle of Britain]] and subsequent [[The Blitz|London Blitz]].<ref name=UN/>\n\n==Content and impact==\nThe Declaration of St James's Palace made three resolutions. In the first, the parties affirmed their alliance, pledging to assist one another in the war against [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] and [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Italy]] and committing \"the utmost of their respective capacities\". The second pledged that the Allies would enter into no [[separate peace]], stating that there could be no peace until the threat of Axis domination was past. The third resolution committed the Allies to the principle of a peace based on the \"willing cooperation of free peoples\" in which \"all may enjoy economic and social security.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://avalon.law.yale.edu/imt/imtjames.asp |title=St. James Agreement; June 12, 1941 |date=2008 |website=[[Avalon Project]] |publisher=[[Yale Law School]] |accessdate=15 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | publication-date =September 1946 | date =June 12, 1941 | year =1941 | title =United Nations Documents, 1941\u20141945 | edition =2nd | place =London | publisher =Royal Institute of International Affairs | page =9 | url =https://archive.org/details/unitednationsdoc031889mbp | accessdate = 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe declaration was the first statement by the Allied Powers expressing a vision for a postwar world order.<ref name=UN/> In August of 1941, Britain and the United States laid out this vision in a more detailed form in the [[Atlantic Charter]]. In September, a second Inter-Allied meeting, which now included [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] ambassador [[Ivan Maisky]], issued a resolution endorsing the Charter. In January 1942 a still larger group of nations issued the [[Declaration by United Nations]], endorsing the same principles initially put forward at St James's and pledging to jointly resist the Axis.<ref name=UN2>{{cite web|title=1942: Declaration of The United Nations|url=https://www.un.org/en/sections/history-united-nations-charter/1942-declaration-united-nations/index.html|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=15 April 2020|date=2015-08-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Allied World War II conferences]]\n* [[German-occupied Europe]]\n{{wikisource|Declaration of St. James's Palace}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Diplomatic history of World War II}}\n\n[[Category:World War II conferences]]\n[[Category:1941 in law]]\n[[Category:1941 in international relations]]\n[[Category:1941 conferences]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom in World War II]]\n[[Category:June 1941 events]]\n[[Category:1941 documents]]\n", "name_user": "Fishal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:punctuation in link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaration_of_St_James%27s_Palace"}
{"title_page": "William Keith of Delny", "text_new": "'''Sir William Keith of Delny''' (d. c. 1605) was a Scottish courtier and keeper of the Royal Wardrobe.\n\nWilliam Keith was a son of Andrew Keith, laird of [[Ravenscraig Castle, Aberdeenshire|Ravenscraig]], Aberdeenshire, and only distantly related to the Earls Marischal. In 1579 he was made a valet in the household of [[James VI of Scotland]].<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, [https://www.euppublishing.com/doi/abs/10.3366/inr.2016.0124 'Sir William Keith of Delny', ''Innes Review'' 67:2 (2016), pp. 138-158], at pp. 140, 142.</ref>\n\nKing James granted William Keith lands in [[Delny]] in Ross in 1586 for good service as Master of the Wardrobe.\n\nIn 1587 Delny was sent to England with [[Robert Melville, 1st Lord Melville|Sir Robert Melville]] of Murdocairny and the [[Patrick Gray, 6th Lord Gray|Master of Gray]] to intercede for the life of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. Their speeches and manner of mediation was said to have been counter-productive.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 9 (Edinburgh, 1915), p. 564.</ref>\n\nIn July 1589 it was expected that Delny and the English courtier [[Roger Aston]] would lose their places at court because they had been supporters of the Master of Gray, who was now out of favour. Their opponents, the followers of the [[George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly|Earl of Huntly]] and [[John Seton, Lord Barns|Sir John Seton]] of [[Barnes Castle|Barnes]] called Aston, Keith, and the [[Walter Stewart, 1st Lord Blantyre|Lord Privy Seal]], \"Queen Elizabeth's pensioners\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 9 (Edinburgh, 1915). p. 448-9, 452, 453: ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (1936), pp. 127-9.</ref>\n\nDelny was in the retinue which accompanied King [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]] to [[Norway]] and [[Denmark]] to collect his future Queen, [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 170-1.</ref> During the trip, the king sacked him as keeper of the wardrobe, allegedly for appearing in richer clothing than himself, and appointed [[George Home, 1st Earl of Dunbar|Sir George Home]] in his stead.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 276, 478.</ref> In the days before Delny lost his place, [[Robert Douglas, Provost of Lincluden]] on 4 April 1590 wrote \"Sir William Keith is lyke to be casin, and to tyne his offices, credit and all.\"<ref>[[Robert Vans Agnew]], ''Correspondence of Sir Patrick Waus of Barnbarroch'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1887), pp. 455-6.</ref> A correspondent of [[Francis Walsingham]] wrote on 5 April 1590 that the Chancellor [[John Maitland, 1st Lord Maitland of Thirlestane|John Maitland of Thirlestane]] aimed to discredit the Earl Marischal and Delny, but Delny was \"wonderfully well beloved\" and had \"ever worn his sword on the right and true side\".<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 3 (London, 1889), p. 403.</ref> \n\nThe English ambassador [[Robert Bowes (diplomat)|Robert Bowes]] noted in July 1591 that Delny \"lay in bed\" once or twice at [[Morham|Morham Tower]] with the owner, the rebellious [[Francis Stewart, 1st Earl of Bothwell]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 551.</ref>\n\nDelny regained royal favour in June 1592 apparently by the intervention of Anne of Denmark in the controversy between the Earl Marischal and the [[Lord Chancellor of Scotland|Lord Chancellor]], [[John Maitland, 1st Lord Maitland of Thirlestane|John Maitland of Thirlestane]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 687.</ref>\n\nDelny became an associate of [[Ludovick Stuart, 2nd Duke of Lennox]]. On 6 May 1593 the Duke and 15 friends subscribed to a frivolous legal document swearing to abstain from wearing gold and silver trimmings on their clothes for a year, and defaulters were to pay for a banquet for all of them at John Killoch's house in Edinburgh. This \"[[Passementerie|passement]] bond\" was in part inspired by cheap counterfeit gold and silver thread used in \"passements great or small, plain or ''\u00e0 jour'', bissets, lilykins, cordons, and fringes\" which quickly discoloured. The signatories included; [[Alexander Home, 1st Lord Home|Lord Home]], the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]], [[Alexander Lindsay, 1st Lord Spynie|Lord Spynie]], the [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Master of Glamis]], [[Thomas Erskine, 1st Earl of Kellie|Sir Thomas Erskine]], [[Walter Stewart of Blantyre]], and [[George Home, Earl of Dunbar|Sir George Home]].<ref>''Historical Manuscripts Commission, Appendix 4th Report: Mrs. Erskine Murray'' (London, 1874), p. 527.</ref>\n\nIn 1594 Delny carried invitations to the [[Masque at the baptism of Prince Henry|baptism and tournament]] at [[Stirling Castle]] for [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]] to the Dutch Republic. Sir [[James Melville of Halhill]] said he was not suited the role because he could not speak French, Latin, or Flemish.<ref>Thomas Thomson, ''Memoirs of his own life by Sir James Melville of Halhill'' (Edinburgh, 1827), p. 411.</ref>\n\nIn April 1597 James VI asked Delny to correspond with Venice, to bolster support for his accession to the throne of England.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1952), p. 507.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Keith, William}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir William Keith of Delny''' (d. c. 1605) was a Scottish courtier and keeper of the Royal Wardrobe.\n\nWilliam Keith was a son of Andrew Keith, laird of [[Ravenscraig Castle, Aberdeenshire|Ravenscraig]], Aberdeenshire, and only distantly related to the Earls Marischal. In 1579 he was made a valet in the household of [[James VI of Scotland]].<ref>Miles Kerr-Peterson, [https://www.euppublishing.com/doi/abs/10.3366/inr.2016.0124 'Sir William Keith of Delny', ''Innes Review'' 67:2 (2016), pp. 138-158], at pp. 140, 142.</ref>\n\nKing James granted William Keith lands in [[Delny]] in Ross in 1586 for good service as Master of the Wardrobe.\n\nIn 1587 Delny was sent to England with [[Robert Melville, 1st Lord Melville|Sir Robert Melville]] of Murdocairny and the [[Patrick Gray, 6th Lord Gray|Master of Gray]] to intercede for the life of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. Their speeches and manner of mediation was said to have been counter-productive.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 9 (Edinburgh, 1915), p. 564.</ref>\n\nIn July 1589 it was expected that Delny and the English courtier [[Roger Aston]] would lose their places at court because they had been supporters of the Master of Gray, who was now out of favour. Their opponents, the followers of the [[George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly|Earl of Huntly]] and [[John Seton, Lord Barns|Sir John Seton]] of [[Barnes Castle|Barnes]] called Aston, Keith, and the [[Walter Stewart, 1st Lord Blantyre|Lord Privy Seal]], \"Queen Elizabeth's pensioners\".<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 9 (Edinburgh, 1915). p. 448-9, 452, 453: ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (1936), pp. 127-9.</ref>\n\nDelny was in the retinue which accompanied King [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]] to [[Norway]] and [[Denmark]] to collect his future Queen, [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 170-1.</ref> During the trip, the king sacked him as keeper of the wardrobe, allegedly for appearing in richer clothing than himself, and appointed [[George Home, 1st Earl of Dunbar|Sir George Home]] in his stead.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 276, 478.</ref> In the days before Delny lost his place, Robert Douglas, Provost of Lincluden on 4 April 1590 wrote \"Sir William Keith is lyke to be casin, and to tyne his offices, credit and all.\"<ref>[[Robert Vans Agnew]], ''Correspondence of Sir Patrick Waus of Barnbarroch'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1887), pp. 455-6.</ref> A correspondent of [[Francis Walsingham]] wrote on 5 April 1590 that the Chancellor [[John Maitland, 1st Lord Maitland of Thirlestane|John Maitland of Thirlestane]] aimed to discredit the Earl Marischal and Delny, but Delny was \"wonderfully well beloved\" and had \"ever worn his sword on the right and true side\".<ref>''HMC Salisbury Hatfield'', vol. 3 (London, 1889), p. 403.</ref> \n\nThe English ambassador [[Robert Bowes (diplomat)|Robert Bowes]] noted in July 1591 that Delny \"lay in bed\" once or twice at [[Morham|Morham Tower]] with the owner, the rebellious [[Francis Stewart, 1st Earl of Bothwell]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 551.</ref>\n\nDelny regained royal favour in June 1592 apparently by the intervention of Anne of Denmark in the controversy between the Earl Marischal and the [[Lord Chancellor of Scotland|Lord Chancellor]], [[John Maitland, 1st Lord Maitland of Thirlestane|John Maitland of Thirlestane]].<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 687.</ref>\n\nDelny became an associate of [[Ludovick Stuart, 2nd Duke of Lennox]]. On 6 May 1593 the Duke and 15 friends subscribed to a frivolous legal document swearing to abstain from wearing gold and silver trimmings on their clothes for a year, and defaulters were to pay for a banquet for all of them at John Killoch's house in Edinburgh. This \"[[Passementerie|passement]] bond\" was in part inspired by cheap counterfeit gold and silver thread used in \"passements great or small, plain or ''\u00e0 jour'', bissets, lilykins, cordons, and fringes\" which quickly discoloured. The signatories included; [[Alexander Home, 1st Lord Home|Lord Home]], the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]], [[Alexander Lindsay, 1st Lord Spynie|Lord Spynie]], the [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Master of Glamis]], [[Thomas Erskine, 1st Earl of Kellie|Sir Thomas Erskine]], [[Walter Stewart of Blantyre]], and [[George Home, Earl of Dunbar|Sir George Home]].<ref>''Historical Manuscripts Commission, Appendix 4th Report: Mrs. Erskine Murray'' (London, 1874), p. 527.</ref>\n\nIn 1594 Delny carried invitations to the [[Masque at the baptism of Prince Henry|baptism and tournament]] at [[Stirling Castle]] for [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]] to the Dutch Republic. Sir [[James Melville of Halhill]] said he was not suited the role because he could not speak French, Latin, or Flemish.<ref>Thomas Thomson, ''Memoirs of his own life by Sir James Melville of Halhill'' (Edinburgh, 1827), p. 411.</ref>\n\nIn April 1597 James VI asked Delny to correspond with Venice, to bolster support for his accession to the throne of England.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1952), p. 507.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Keith, William}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Keith_of_Delny"}
