| seating_capacity    = 33,500<ref>{{cite web|title=Stadium History|work=Winnipeg Blue Bombers|url=https://www.bluebombers.com/stadium-history/|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>(expandable to 40,000)([[Canadian football|football]])\n| suites              = 46<ref>{{cite news |author = Brent Bellamy |title = The Jets \u2013 and a big-league stadium, too |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 10 October 2011 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/columnists/the-jets----and-a--big-league-stadium-too-131439343.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''IG Field''', formerly '''Investors Group Field''',<ref>{{cite web |last=Dacey |first=Elisha |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5262271/investors-group-field-changing-name-to-ig-field/ |title=Investors Group Field changing name to IG Field |work=Global News |date=May 10, 2019 |access-date=June 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514002548/https://globalnews.ca/news/5262271/investors-group-field-changing-name-to-ig-field/ |archive-date=May 14, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> is a football stadium in [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada.<ref>{{cite news |title = Blue Bombers to get new stadium and new owner |publisher = TSN |url = https://www.tsn.ca/cfl/story/?id=273524|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> The stadium, which opened in 2013, is located on the [[University of Manitoba]] campus next to [[University Stadium (Winnipeg)|University Stadium]].<ref name=\"Ready for 2012\">{{cite web|title=Winnipeg football stadium to be ready for 2012 season|url=http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id43587|publisher=Reed Business Information|access-date=14 July 2013|author=Peter Caulfield|date=March 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503073826/http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id43587|archive-date=3 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Owned by Triple B Stadium Inc., a [[consortium]] of the City of Winnipeg, the Province of Manitoba, the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers|Winnipeg Football Club]] and the University of Manitoba,<ref name=\"CBC Lawsuit\">{{cite news |author = Sean Kavanagh |title = Lawsuit alleges Winnipeg's IGF stadium leaky, mouldy |publisher = CBC Manitoba|date = 5 March 2015 |url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/lawsuit-alleges-winnipeg-s-igf-stadium-leaky-mouldy-1.2983608|accessdate=2015-03-05}}</ref> the stadium is home to the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL), [[Valour FC]] of the [[Canadian Premier League]] (CPL), the [[University of Manitoba Bisons]] [[U Sports football|football]] team, and the [[Winnipeg Rifles]] ([[CJFL]]).\n\nThe stadium has a capacity of 33,500 and is partially covered. The stadium contains a corrugated metal roof, restaurant, 52 suites, walk of fame and other amenities.\n\n==History==\n\n===Development===\nThe owners of [[Canad Inns]], a Winnipeg-based hotel business and naming rights holder for the [[Canad Inns Stadium|Blue Bombers' former stadium]], forwarded a plan in 2007 to redevelop the entire site for commercial use and construct a football stadium for the Blue Bombers in another location. This proposal, although rejected in favour of [[David Asper]]'s plan, called for a $265&nbsp;million stadium at the former Public Markets site in the St. Boniface industrial park, which Canad Inns purchased from the city. The domed stadium would have been part of a $500&nbsp;million complex that would have included a four-star hotel and an indoor water park.<ref name=\"CanadProp\">{{cite news |title = Canad Inns proposes domed stadium for Winnipeg |publisher = CBC News|date = 10 April 2007 |url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/canad-inns-proposes-domed-stadium-for-winnipeg-1.642575|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\nDavid Asper's original proposal involved both [[Government of Canada|federal]] and [[Government of Manitoba|provincial]] government financial contributions ($40&nbsp;million each), as well as a transfer of assets (the publicly owned Blue Bomber franchise itself will be transferred into Asper's control, and the existing undeveloped commercial real estate surrounding the stadium). As part of Creswin's commitment to the project, Asper pledged to contribute $65&nbsp;million toward the Maroons Road development. In addition to stadium construction, the Asper proposal included {{convert|217000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of retail development and a two-level parking facility.\n\n[[File:Investors Group Field logo.png|right|thumb|Logo from 2013 to 2019]]\n\nThe Blue Bombers' board of directors investigated the possibility of rebuilding or substantially upgrading the existing stadium, largely with funds generated from the sale or lease of the adjacent commercial lands<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcgowanrussell.com/projects/wbb.php|title=McGowan Russell Group|website=Mcgowanrussell.com|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref> (the team holds the right to develop this property itself as part of its refinancing agreement with the city of Winnipeg and province of Manitoba). However, being a community owned business, the Bombers organization would have had difficulty in accessing the capital required to move forward with such plans directly. The board placed its plans on hold pending the outcome of Asper's proposal.\n\nThe government was unwilling to grant Asper the $40&nbsp;million at both the provincial and federal levels because it believed the money to be more of a gift than a grant. Creswin drew up a second proposal, where the same 30,000\u201340,000-seat stadium would be built instead in south Point Douglas.<ref>{{cite news |title = Asper unveils new stadium vision |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date = 27 June 2008 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/historic/32918854.html |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> This new plan, they said, would greatly aid in urban renewal in what is the poorest neighborhood in Winnipeg. There was also a state-of-the-art water park and hotel, commercial buildings and several other new buildings in the multimillion-dollar proposal. However, there was controversy as well because south Point Douglas is an avid art community, and many of the residents did not want their character buildings to be destroyed or suffer the loss of their homes.<ref>{{cite news |author = Gary Lawless |title = Selinger grabs ball on stadium |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date = 27 March 2010 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/selinger-grabs-ball-on-stadium-89319412.html |accessdate=2010-04-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Winnipeg Nov 2 2013 Max Hall.JPG|thumb|An in-game photo of the Winnipeg Blue Bombers on offence against the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]].]]\nA letter of intent was signed on September 13, 2009, between Asper's Creswin Properties and the University of Manitoba, allowing planning to continue for a stadium at the intersection of Chancellor Matheson Drive and University Crescent. The site is adjacent to the current [[University Stadium (Winnipeg)|University Stadium]], which was built for the 1967 Pan American Games. The new proposal includes the construction of a 33,422-seat stadium, renovation of the existing stadium, and a world-class fitness facility. Inflatable \"bubbles\" covering the playing field were also proposed for both stadiums during the winter months. The cost of the new stadium, was projected to be $115&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/bombers-stadium-costs-climb-higher-1.894278|title=Bombers stadium costs climb higher|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe new stadium would also be home of the [[University of Manitoba Bisons]] football team. The design allows for expansion to 40,000 seats for the [[Grey Cup]] (however for [[2015 Grey Cup]] 36,500 seats were available). The stadium was approved on 2 April 2009. The province of Manitoba later agreed to loan David Asper $90&nbsp;million in order to guarantee the project would break ground in 2010 and ensure the stadium would open for 2012.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bartley Kives |title=Manitoba gives $90M loan for new Bombers stadium |newspaper=[[National Post]] |date=31 March 2010 |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/story.html?id=2748771 |accessdate=2010-04-07 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author = Ed Tait |title =Sod turns on new stadium |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date =20 May 2010 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/sod-turns-on-new-stadium-94403949.html |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> CFL Commissioner [[Mark Cohon]], Premier of Manitoba [[Greg Selinger]], David Asper, Mayor of Winnipeg [[Sam Katz]] and U of M President David Barnard officially broke ground at the site on May 20, 2010.\n[[File:Investors Group CANnwt vs USnwt.png|thumb|right|200px|The Canada vs USA women's soccer game exhibition played in May, 2014 to a 1\u20131 draw.]]\n\nAsper and Creswin were removed from the deal as they made significant changes to the stadium design which broke the original contract.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/football/story/2010/12/13/mb-stadium-financing-details-bombers-winnipeg.html |title=Asper out of Blue Bomber stadium plans|date=December 13, 2010|publisher=[[CBC Sports]]|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> The revised cost amounted to $190&nbsp;million, with the Winnipeg Blue Bombers paying back $85&nbsp;million, and the provincial and city levels of government splitting the rest of the costs as previously proposed.\n\n===Controversy===\nThe new stadium was expected to be ready for the start of the 2012 season.<ref name=\"winnipegsun.com\">{{cite news|author = Ross Romaniuk | url=http://www.winnipegsun.com/2011/08/26/blue-bombers-stadium-taking-shape |title= Blue Bombers stadium taking shape |date= 2011-09-07 |publisher=[[Winnipeg Sun]]|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> However, on May 2, 2012, the Blue Bombers announced that because of construction delays, the stadium would not be ready until September, thus forcing the team to play four or five home games at [[Canad Inns Stadium]] to start the season.<ref>{{cite news |author = Gary Lawless and Bruce Owen |title = First game in new stadium could be as early as Sept. 9: Bombers |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 25 May 2012 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/First-game-in-new-stadium-to-be-Sept-21-Bombers-149833095.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> In June 2012, it was announced the stadium would not open until the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bombers to play entire season at Canad Inns Stadium |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/159204945.html |newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press  |date=June 15, 2012}}</ref> In December 2013, it was reported the previously-announced inflatable dome had been dropped from the plans in 2012.<ref>{{cite news | author = Bartley Kives | title = Winter stadium bubble deemed impractical |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date =6 December 2013 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/Winter-stadium-bubble-deemed-impractical-234803401.html |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the builder, Stuart Olson Dominion, put a $1.9&nbsp;million lien on the stadium because it claimed it was owed for some of the cost overruns.<ref>{{cite news |author = Bartley Kives |title = Construction firm slaps lien on stadium |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 10 January 2014 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/construction-firm-slaps-lien-on-stadium-239548191.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> This dispute was resolved later that year, with the province contributing an additional $1.5&nbsp;million to cover additional costs incurred during construction, bringing the total cost to $210&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"cost\"/>\n\nOn March 4, 2015, the stadium's ownership group, Triple B Stadium Inc., announced its intention to sue architect Ray Wan and builder Stuart Olson Dominion.<ref>{{cite news |author = Bartley Kives |title = Stadium owner to sue architect, builder over water drainage, insulation problems |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 4 March 2015 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/295009101.html|accessdate=2015-03-05}}</ref> In the statement of claim, it cited water damage caused by insufficient drainage in the building, as well as inadequate insulation and \"extensive\" cracking in the concrete among a total of 42 deficiencies.<ref name=\"CBC Lawsuit\"/> On April 23, Stuart Olson filed a statement of defence denying most of Triple B's allegations, stating the shell company \u2014 which represents the city, province, university and the Winnipeg Football Club \u2014 made all the key construction decisions, in concert with the province, which paid for most of the construction up front. Stuart Olson also alleged political and financial factors led the province to rush the job and reduce its budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/Strife-over-Investors-Group-Field-is-hurting-the-Bombers-303945721.html|title=Strife over Investors Group Field is hurting the Bombers|website=Winnipegfreepress.com|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 27, 2015, the government of Manitoba announced it would pay $35&nbsp;million to repair the stadium. It would then seek compensation for this further outlay of money from the proceeds of the aforementioned lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/premier-greg-selinger-defends-35m-loan-guarantee-to-fix-investors-group-field-1.3291117|title=Premier Greg Selinger defends $35M loan guarantee to fix Investors Group Field|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notable events==\n===Canadian football===\nThe Blue Bombers played their first home game at Investors Group Field on June 27, 2013, losing 38\u201333 to the [[Montreal Alouettes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=CFL releases 2013 regular season schedule | url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/football/cfl/story/2013/03/05/sp-cfl-season-schedule-2013.html|publisher=CBC|date=March 5, 2013 | accessdate = 2014-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author = Paul Wiecek |title = Bombers late to the party |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 28 June 2013 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/bombers-late-to-the-party-213464451.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, it was confirmed that Investors Group Field would host the [[103rd Grey Cup|2015 Grey Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |author = Judy Owen |title = CFL to show off Investors Group Field as Winnipeg picked to host 2015 Grey Cup |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 26 March 2014 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/cfl/cfl-to-show-off-investors-group-field-as-winnipeg-picked-to-host-2015-grey-cup-252491901.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===American football===\nIG Field hosted an [[NFL]] [[NFL preseason|preseason game]] between the [[Green Bay Packers]] and [[Oakland Raiders]] on August 22, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/sports/winnipeg-to-host-nfl-pre-season-game-between-raiders-and-packers-1.4454172|title=Winnipeg to host NFL pre-season game between Raiders and Packers|website=CTV News Winnipeg|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/regina-ready-for-an-nfl-game-but-logistics-need-to-work-mayor-says-1.5076956|title=Attempt to host NFL preseason game in Regina stopped short of the goal line|work=CBC News|date=March 29, 2019|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref> The teams largely [[resting the starters|avoided playing starters]] in the game. In attempting to move the goalposts back five yards from each's position to accommodate their NFL positioning (behind the endzone, as is customary in the American game), it left holes in each end zone that the NFL deemed a safety hazard; since this discovery came too late to put the goalposts back and repaint the field, each ten-yard line was hastily converted to a goal line by adding pylons to shorten the field to 80 yards (from the standard 100 yard field/10 yard endzones used for American rules football), and kickoffs were eliminated.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Breech |first1=John |title=Packers, Raiders forced to play on shortened field with different rules due to unsafe conditions in Canada |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/packers-raiders-forced-to-play-on-shortened-field-with-different-rules-due-to-unsafe-conditions-in-canada/ |publisher=CBS Sports. |accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref> The changes did not have an appreciable impact on the game according to Raiders coach [[Jon Gruden]], and most of the coaches and players otherwise praised IG Field's playing surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001043417/article/raiders-packers-play-preseason-game-on-80yard-field|title=Raiders, Packers play preseason game on 80-yard field|work=NFL.com|first=Grant|last=Gordon|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/football/nfl/winnipegs-nfl-pre-season-game-changed-80-yard-field-due-conditions/|title=Raiders beat Packers in Winnipeg on reconfigured 80-yard field|agency=Canadian Press|publisher=Sportsnet|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Date \n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Away\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Score\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Home\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Ref.\n|-\n| August 22, 2019 || [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] || 21\u201322 || '''[[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]]''' || [https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2019082255/2019/PRE3/packers@raiders Recap]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Hockey===\nInvestors Group Field hosted the fourth instalment of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL)'s [[2016 Heritage Classic|Heritage Classic]] on October 23, 2016, in which the [[Winnipeg Jets]] lost 3\u20130 to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] in front of a sold-out crowd. The Classic's customary alumni game was played a day earlier and featured players from [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|the former Jets franchise]] returning to Winnipeg to play the Oilers alumni team. The Jets alumni, led by [[Teemu Sel\u00e4nne]] and [[Dale Hawerchuk]], defeated [[Wayne Gretzky]]'s Oilers squad 6\u20135 in a shootout.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3020054/winnipeg-jets-beat-edmonton-oilers-6-5-at-heritage-classic-alumni-game/|title=Winnipeg Jets beat Edmonton Oilers 6-5 at Heritage Classic alumni game|date=October 22, 2016|publisher=GlobalNews.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Association football===\nThe [[Canada women's national soccer team]] played their first match at Investors Group Field on May 8, 2014, against the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]], with the result in a tie (1\u20131); this match was the stadium's first soccer game.<ref>{{cite news |title=World's best can't beat Canada |author=Ed Tait |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/soccer/worlds-best-cant-beat-canada-258585901.html |newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date=May 9, 2014}}</ref> In June 2015, Winnipeg was one of six Canadian cities that hosted the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|FIFA Women's World Cup]]. The first four matches of [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Group D|Group D]]\u2014between the United States, [[Australia women's national soccer team|Australia]], [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]] and [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigeria]]\u2014were contested at Investors Group Field, followed by three matches from various other groups.<ref>{{cite news |author = Ed Tait |title = Winnipeg to host FIFA Women's World Cup |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date =5 May 2012 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/soccer/Winnipeg-to-host-FIFA-Womens-World-Cup-150207165.html | accessdate = 2012-05-04}}</ref> Due to [[FIFA]]'s policy regarding commercial sponsorship of stadium names, the Investors Group Field was referred to as \"Winnipeg Stadium\" during the World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/destination/cities/city=18908/index.html |title=FIFA Women's World Cup Canada 2015\u2122 Destination: Winnipeg |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> The FIFA World Cup will return to Winnipeg in 2026 for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|Men's World Cup]]\n\nIn 2019, IG Field became the home of [[Valour FC]] in the [[Canadian Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/winnipeg-soccer-franchise-fc-valour-1.4694586|title='Total excitement' as Canadian Premier League announces Valour FC, Winnipeg's new professional soccer team|last=|first=|date=June 6, 2018|work=Canadian Premier League|access-date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''2015 FIFA Women's World Cup'''\n{{Clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:left; width:85%;\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Time ([[Central Daylight Time|CDT]])\n!Team #1\n!Result\n!Team #2\n!Round\n!Attendance\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|8 June 2015||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 15:00||{{fbw|SWE}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\u20133 ||{{fbw|NGA}} ||rowspan=4|Group D ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|31,148\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|18:30||{{fbw|USA}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\u20131 ||{{fbw|AUS}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|31,148\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|12 June 2015||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16:00||{{fbw|AUS}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\u20130 ||{{fbw|NGA}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|32,716\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|19:00||{{fbw|USA}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20130||{{fbw|SWE}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|32,716\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2|15 June 2015||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 15:00||{{fbw|GER}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\u20130 ||{{fbw|THA}} ||Group B ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|26,191\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 18:30||{{fbw|CHN}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\u20132 ||{{fbw|NZL}} ||Group A ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|26,191\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |16 June 2015||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16:00||{{fbw|ECU}} ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 0\u20131 ||{{fbw|JPN}} ||Group C ||style=\"text-align:center;\"|14,522\n|-\n|}\n\n===Concerts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! width=12% style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Date \n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Artist(s) \n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Opening act(s) \n! width=16% style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Tour \n! width=10% style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Tickets sold \n| width=10% style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Revenue\n! width=20% style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Additional notes \n|-\n| June 22, 2013 || [[Taylor Swift]] || [[Ed Sheeran]]<br/>[[Austin Mahone]]<br/>[[Joel Crouse]] || [[The Red Tour]] || 33,061 / 33,061 || $3,175,430 || The stadium's first concert.<ref>{{cite news| author = Bartley Kives |title=Fewer bums in seats at Investors Group Field | url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/fewer-bums-in-seats-at-new-stadium-182643051.html|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|date=December 8, 2012|accessdate = 2014-06-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| August 12, 2013 || [[Paul McCartney]] || \u2014 || [[Out There (tour)|Out There]] || 30,149 / 30,149 || $4,079,490 || \"Mull of Kintyre\" was performed with the City of Winnipeg Police Pipe Band.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/Paul-McCartney-to-play-Winnipeg-Aug-12-204106261.html|title=Paul McCartney to play Winnipeg Aug. 12|date=22 April 2013|accessdate=2014-06-01|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press}}</ref>\n|-\n| July 27, 2014 || [[Beyonc\u00e9]]<br/>[[Jay Z]] || \u2014 || [[On the Run Tour (Beyonc\u00e9 and Jay-Z)|On the Run Tour]] || 29,542 / 29,542 || $3,187,580 || \n|-\n| July 24, 2015 || [[One Direction]] || [[Icona Pop]] || [[On the Road Again Tour]] || 24,991 / 24,991 || $1,872,587 || The band performed a cover of \"Happy Birthday\" by [[Mildred J. Hill]] and [[Liam Payne]] and \"Hero\" by [[Enrique Iglesias]].\n|-\n| September 17, 2015 || [[AC/DC]] || [[Vintage Trouble]] || [[Rock or Bust World Tour]] || 34,000 / 34,000 || \u2014 || \n|-\n| August 24, 2017 || [[Guns N' Roses]] || [[Our Lady Peace]] || [[Not In This Lifetime... Tour]] || 30,741 / 30,741 || $3,008,250 || A cover of [[Black Hole Sun]] by [[Soundgarden]] was performed as a tribute to [[Chris Cornell]]\n|}\n\n===Other events===\nThe stadium hosted its first event on May 26, 2013, with the One Heart Winnipeg celebration, a multi-denominational church service organized by several local church groups.<ref>{{cite news |title=Church service a first look at Bombers' new digs |author=Alexandra Hall |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/stadium-a-blessing-209039261.html |newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date=May 27, 2013 | accessdate = 2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.bluebombers.com/stadium}}\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-sta|et}}}}\n{{succession box\n | title = Home of the<br/>[[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n | years = 2013\u2013present\n | before = [[Canad Inns Stadium]]\n | after = Current stadium\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title = Home of the [[Manitoba Bisons]] football team\n | years = 2013\u2013present\n | before = [[University Stadium (Winnipeg)|University Stadium]]\n | after = Current stadium\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Winnipeg Blue Bombers}}\n{{Valour FC}}\n{{CFL Stadiums}}\n{{Canadian Premier League stadiums}}\n{{2015 FIFA Women's World Cup stadiums}}\n\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 2013]]\n[[Category:Canadian Football League venues]]\n[[Category:Canadian football venues in Manitoba]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Soccer venues in Manitoba]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:University sports venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n[[Category:University of Manitoba]]\n[[Category:Canadian football in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Canadian Premier League stadiums]]\n[[Category:Valour FC]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name        = IG Field\n| logo_image          = IG_Field_(logo).svg\n| image               = Investors Group Field 2014.png\n| image_size = 260px\n| caption             = IG Field in 2014\n| location            = [[University of Manitoba]], 315 Chancellor Matheson Road, [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|49|48|28|N|97|8|35|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map         = Canada Manitoba#Canada\n| pushpin_relief      = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Manitoba##Location in Canada\n| broke_ground        = May 20, 2010\n| opened              = May 26, 2013\n| closed              = \n| demolished          = \n| owner               = Triple B Stadium Inc.\n| operator            = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n| surface             = [[FieldTurf]] Revolution<ref name=\"IGF Information\">{{cite web |title = Stadium Information  |publisher = www.bluebombers.com |url = http://www.bluebombers.com/stadium-information|accessdate=2014-11-11}}</ref>\n| construction_cost   = [[Canadian Dollar|$]]210 million\n| builder   = Stuart Olson Dominion Construction\n| architect           = Raymond S.C Wan\n| cost                = $210 million<ref name=\"cost\">{{cite news |title = Stadium dispute resolved, final price tag $210 million |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 2 May 2014 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/stadium-dispute-resolved-final-price-tag-210-million-257622631.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n| former_names        = Investors Group Field {{small|(2013\u201318)}}\n| tenants             = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]] ([[Canadian Football League|CFL]]) (2013\u2013present)<br/>[[Manitoba Bisons]] ([[U Sports]]) (2013\u2013present)<br/>[[Winnipeg Rifles]] ([[Canadian Junior Football League|CJFL]]) (2013\u2013present)<br/>[[Valour FC]] ([[Canadian Premier League|CPL]]) (2019\u2013present)\n| seating_capacity    = 33,500<ref>{{cite web|title=Stadium History|work=Winnipeg Blue Bombers|url=https://www.bluebombers.com/stadium-history/|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref>(expandable to 40,000)([[Canadian football|football]])\n| suites              = 46<ref>{{cite news |author = Brent Bellamy |title = The Jets \u2013 and a big-league stadium, too |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 10 October 2011 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/opinion/columnists/the-jets----and-a--big-league-stadium-too-131439343.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''IG Field''', formerly '''Investors Group Field''',<ref>{{cite web |last=Dacey |first=Elisha |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5262271/investors-group-field-changing-name-to-ig-field/ |title=Investors Group Field changing name to IG Field |work=Global News |date=May 10, 2019 |access-date=June 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514002548/https://globalnews.ca/news/5262271/investors-group-field-changing-name-to-ig-field/ |archive-date=May 14, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref> is a football stadium in [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada.<ref>{{cite news |title = Blue Bombers to get new stadium and new owner |publisher = TSN |url = https://www.tsn.ca/cfl/story/?id=273524|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> The stadium, which opened in 2013, is located on the [[University of Manitoba]] campus next to [[University Stadium (Winnipeg)|University Stadium]].<ref name=\"Ready for 2012\">{{cite web|title=Winnipeg football stadium to be ready for 2012 season|url=http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id43587|publisher=Reed Business Information|access-date=14 July 2013|author=Peter Caulfield|date=March 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503073826/http://www.journalofcommerce.com/article/id43587|archive-date=3 May 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Owned by Triple B Stadium Inc., a [[consortium]] of the City of Winnipeg, the Province of Manitoba, the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers|Winnipeg Football Club]] and the University of Manitoba,<ref name=\"CBC Lawsuit\">{{cite news |author = Sean Kavanagh |title = Lawsuit alleges Winnipeg's IGF stadium leaky, mouldy |publisher = CBC Manitoba|date = 5 March 2015 |url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/lawsuit-alleges-winnipeg-s-igf-stadium-leaky-mouldy-1.2983608|accessdate=2015-03-05}}</ref> the stadium is home to the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL), [[Valour FC]] of the [[Canadian Premier League]] (CPL), the [[University of Manitoba Bisons]] [[U Sports football|football]] team, and the [[Winnipeg Rifles]] ([[CJFL]]).\n\nThe stadium has a capacity of 33,500 and is partially covered. The stadium contains a corrugated metal roof, restaurant, 52 suites, walk of fame and other amenities.\n\n==History==\n\n===Development===\nThe owners of [[Canad Inns]], a Winnipeg-based hotel business and naming rights holder for the [[Canad Inns Stadium|Blue Bombers' former stadium]], forwarded a plan in 2007 to redevelop the entire site for commercial use and construct a football stadium for the Blue Bombers in another location. This proposal, although rejected in favour of [[David Asper]]'s plan, called for a $265&nbsp;million stadium at the former Public Markets site in the St. Boniface industrial park, which Canad Inns purchased from the city. The domed stadium would have been part of a $500&nbsp;million complex that would have included a four-star hotel and an indoor water park.<ref name=\"CanadProp\">{{cite news |title = Canad Inns proposes domed stadium for Winnipeg |publisher = CBC News|date = 10 April 2007 |url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/canad-inns-proposes-domed-stadium-for-winnipeg-1.642575|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\nDavid Asper's original proposal involved both [[Government of Canada|federal]] and [[Government of Manitoba|provincial]] government financial contributions ($40&nbsp;million each), as well as a transfer of assets (the publicly owned Blue Bomber franchise itself will be transferred into Asper's control, and the existing undeveloped commercial real estate surrounding the stadium). As part of Creswin's commitment to the project, Asper pledged to contribute $65&nbsp;million toward the Maroons Road development. In addition to stadium construction, the Asper proposal included {{convert|217000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of retail development and a two-level parking facility.\n\n[[File:Investors Group Field logo.png|right|thumb|Logo from 2013 to 2019]]\n\nThe Blue Bombers' board of directors investigated the possibility of rebuilding or substantially upgrading the existing stadium, largely with funds generated from the sale or lease of the adjacent commercial lands<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcgowanrussell.com/projects/wbb.php|title=McGowan Russell Group|website=Mcgowanrussell.com|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref> (the team holds the right to develop this property itself as part of its refinancing agreement with the city of Winnipeg and province of Manitoba). However, being a community owned business, the Bombers organization would have had difficulty in accessing the capital required to move forward with such plans directly. The board placed its plans on hold pending the outcome of Asper's proposal.\n\nThe government was unwilling to grant Asper the $40&nbsp;million at both the provincial and federal levels because it believed the money to be more of a gift than a grant. Creswin drew up a second proposal, where the same 30,000\u201340,000-seat stadium would be built instead in south Point Douglas.<ref>{{cite news |title = Asper unveils new stadium vision |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date = 27 June 2008 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/historic/32918854.html |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> This new plan, they said, would greatly aid in urban renewal in what is the poorest neighborhood in Winnipeg. There was also a state-of-the-art water park and hotel, commercial buildings and several other new buildings in the multimillion-dollar proposal. However, there was controversy as well because south Point Douglas is an avid art community, and many of the residents did not want their character buildings to be destroyed or suffer the loss of their homes.<ref>{{cite news |author = Gary Lawless |title = Selinger grabs ball on stadium |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date = 27 March 2010 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/selinger-grabs-ball-on-stadium-89319412.html |accessdate=2010-04-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Winnipeg Nov 2 2013 Max Hall.JPG|thumb|An in-game photo of the Winnipeg Blue Bombers on offence against the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]].]]\nA letter of intent was signed on September 13, 2009, between Asper's Creswin Properties and the University of Manitoba, allowing planning to continue for a stadium at the intersection of Chancellor Matheson Drive and University Crescent. The site is adjacent to the current [[University Stadium (Winnipeg)|University Stadium]], which was built for the 1967 Pan American Games. The new proposal includes the construction of a 33,422-seat stadium, renovation of the existing stadium, and a world-class fitness facility. Inflatable \"bubbles\" covering the playing field were also proposed for both stadiums during the winter months. The cost of the new stadium, was projected to be $115&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/bombers-stadium-costs-climb-higher-1.894278|title=Bombers stadium costs climb higher|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe new stadium would also be home of the [[University of Manitoba Bisons]] football team. The design allows for expansion to 40,000 seats for the [[Grey Cup]] (however for [[2015 Grey Cup]] 36,500 seats were available). The stadium was approved on 2 April 2009. The province of Manitoba later agreed to loan David Asper $90&nbsp;million in order to guarantee the project would break ground in 2010 and ensure the stadium would open for 2012.<ref>{{cite news|author=Bartley Kives |title=Manitoba gives $90M loan for new Bombers stadium |newspaper=[[National Post]] |date=31 March 2010 |url=https://nationalpost.com/sports/story.html?id=2748771 |accessdate=2010-04-07 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author = Ed Tait |title =Sod turns on new stadium |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date =20 May 2010 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/sod-turns-on-new-stadium-94403949.html |accessdate=2010-05-20}}</ref> CFL Commissioner [[Mark Cohon]], Premier of Manitoba [[Greg Selinger]], David Asper, Mayor of Winnipeg [[Sam Katz]] and U of M President David Barnard officially broke ground at the site on May 20, 2010.\n[[File:Investors Group CANnwt vs USnwt.png|thumb|right|200px|The Canada vs USA women's soccer game exhibition played in May, 2014 to a 1\u20131 draw.]]\n\nAsper and Creswin were removed from the deal as they made significant changes to the stadium design which broke the original contract.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/football/story/2010/12/13/mb-stadium-financing-details-bombers-winnipeg.html |title=Asper out of Blue Bomber stadium plans|date=December 13, 2010|publisher=[[CBC Sports]]|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> The revised cost amounted to $190&nbsp;million, with the Winnipeg Blue Bombers paying back $85&nbsp;million, and the provincial and city levels of government splitting the rest of the costs as previously proposed.\n\n===Controversy===\nThe new stadium was expected to be ready for the start of the 2012 season.<ref name=\"winnipegsun.com\">{{cite news|author = Ross Romaniuk | url=http://www.winnipegsun.com/2011/08/26/blue-bombers-stadium-taking-shape |title= Blue Bombers stadium taking shape |date= 2011-09-07 |publisher=[[Winnipeg Sun]]|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> However, on May 2, 2012, the Blue Bombers announced that because of construction delays, the stadium would not be ready until September, thus forcing the team to play four or five home games at [[Canad Inns Stadium]] to start the season.<ref>{{cite news |author = Gary Lawless and Bruce Owen |title = First game in new stadium could be as early as Sept. 9: Bombers |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 25 May 2012 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/First-game-in-new-stadium-to-be-Sept-21-Bombers-149833095.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> In June 2012, it was announced the stadium would not open until the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bombers to play entire season at Canad Inns Stadium |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/159204945.html |newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press  |date=June 15, 2012}}</ref> In December 2013, it was reported the previously-announced inflatable dome had been dropped from the plans in 2012.<ref>{{cite news | author = Bartley Kives | title = Winter stadium bubble deemed impractical |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date =6 December 2013 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/Winter-stadium-bubble-deemed-impractical-234803401.html |accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the builder, Stuart Olson Dominion, put a $1.9&nbsp;million lien on the stadium because it claimed it was owed for some of the cost overruns.<ref>{{cite news |author = Bartley Kives |title = Construction firm slaps lien on stadium |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 10 January 2014 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/construction-firm-slaps-lien-on-stadium-239548191.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref> This dispute was resolved later that year, with the province contributing an additional $1.5&nbsp;million to cover additional costs incurred during construction, bringing the total cost to $210&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"cost\"/>\n\nOn March 4, 2015, the stadium's ownership group, Triple B Stadium Inc., announced its intention to sue architect Ray Wan and builder Stuart Olson Dominion.<ref>{{cite news |author = Bartley Kives |title = Stadium owner to sue architect, builder over water drainage, insulation problems |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 4 March 2015 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/295009101.html|accessdate=2015-03-05}}</ref> In the statement of claim, it cited water damage caused by insufficient drainage in the building, as well as inadequate insulation and \"extensive\" cracking in the concrete among a total of 42 deficiencies.<ref name=\"CBC Lawsuit\"/> On April 23, Stuart Olson filed a statement of defence denying most of Triple B's allegations, stating the shell company \u2014 which represents the city, province, university and the Winnipeg Football Club \u2014 made all the key construction decisions, in concert with the province, which paid for most of the construction up front. Stuart Olson also alleged political and financial factors led the province to rush the job and reduce its budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/Strife-over-Investors-Group-Field-is-hurting-the-Bombers-303945721.html|title=Strife over Investors Group Field is hurting the Bombers|website=Winnipegfreepress.com|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 27, 2015, the government of Manitoba announced it would pay $35&nbsp;million to repair the stadium. It would then seek compensation for this further outlay of money from the proceeds of the aforementioned lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/premier-greg-selinger-defends-35m-loan-guarantee-to-fix-investors-group-field-1.3291117|title=Premier Greg Selinger defends $35M loan guarantee to fix Investors Group Field|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notable events==\n===Canadian football===\nThe Blue Bombers played their first home game at Investors Group Field on June 27, 2013, losing 38\u201333 to the [[Montreal Alouettes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=CFL releases 2013 regular season schedule | url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/football/cfl/story/2013/03/05/sp-cfl-season-schedule-2013.html|publisher=CBC|date=March 5, 2013 | accessdate = 2014-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author = Paul Wiecek |title = Bombers late to the party |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 28 June 2013 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/bombers-late-to-the-party-213464451.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, it was confirmed that Investors Group Field would host the [[103rd Grey Cup|2015 Grey Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |author = Judy Owen |title = CFL to show off Investors Group Field as Winnipeg picked to host 2015 Grey Cup |newspaper = Winnipeg Free Press|date = 26 March 2014 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/cfl/cfl-to-show-off-investors-group-field-as-winnipeg-picked-to-host-2015-grey-cup-252491901.html|accessdate=2014-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===American football===\nIG Field hosted an [[NFL]] [[NFL preseason|preseason game]] between the [[Green Bay Packers]] and [[Oakland Raiders]] on August 22, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/sports/winnipeg-to-host-nfl-pre-season-game-between-raiders-and-packers-1.4454172|title=Winnipeg to host NFL pre-season game between Raiders and Packers|website=CTV News Winnipeg|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/regina-ready-for-an-nfl-game-but-logistics-need-to-work-mayor-says-1.5076956|title=Attempt to host NFL preseason game in Regina stopped short of the goal line|work=CBC News|date=March 29, 2019|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref> The teams largely [[resting the starters|avoided playing starters]] in the game. In attempting to move the goalposts back five yards from each's position to accommodate their NFL positioning (behind the endzone, as is customary in the American game), it left holes in each end zone that the NFL deemed a safety hazard; since this discovery came too late to put the goalposts back and repaint the field, each ten-yard line was hastily converted to a goal line by adding pylons to shorten the field to 80 yards (from the standard 100 yard field/10 yard endzones used for American rules football), and kickoffs were eliminated.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Breech |first1=John |title=Packers, Raiders forced to play on shortened field with different rules due to unsafe conditions in Canada |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/packers-raiders-forced-to-play-on-shortened-field-with-different-rules-due-to-unsafe-conditions-in-canada/ |publisher=CBS Sports. |accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref> The changes did not have an appreciable impact on the game according to Raiders coach [[Jon Gruden]], and most of the coaches and players otherwise praised IG Field's playing surface.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001043417/article/raiders-packers-play-preseason-game-on-80yard-field|title=Raiders, Packers play preseason game on 80-yard field|work=NFL.com|first=Grant|last=Gordon|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/football/nfl/winnipegs-nfl-pre-season-game-changed-80-yard-field-due-conditions/|title=Raiders beat Packers in Winnipeg on reconfigured 80-yard field|agency=Canadian Press|publisher=Sportsnet|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Date \n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Away\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Score\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Home\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#1E3D79; color:white; border:2px solid #BE955B;\"|Ref.\n|-\n| August 22, 2019 || [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] || 21\u201322 || '''[[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]]''' || [https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2019082255/2019/PRE3/packers@raiders Recap]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Hockey===\nInvestors Group Field hosted the fourth instalment of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL)'s [[2016 Heritage Classic|Heritage Classic]] on October 23, 2016, in which the [[Winnipeg Jets]] lost 3\u20130 to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] in front of a sold-out crowd. The Classic's customary alumni game was played a day earlier and featured players from [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|the former Jets franchise]] returning to Winnipeg to play the Oilers alumni team. The Jets alumni, led by [[Teemu Sel\u00e4nne]] and [[Dale Hawerchuk]], defeated [[Wayne Gretzky]]'s Oilers squad 6\u20135 in a shootout.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3020054/winnipeg-jets-beat-edmonton-oilers-6-5-at-heritage-classic-alumni-game/|title=Winnipeg Jets beat Edmonton Oilers 6-5 at Heritage Classic alumni game|date=October 22, 2016|publisher=GlobalNews.ca}}</ref>\n\n===Association football===\nThe [[Canada women's national soccer team]] played their first match at Investors Group Field on May 8, 2014, against the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]], with the result in a tie (1\u20131); this match was the stadium's first soccer game.<ref>{{cite news |title=World's best can't beat Canada |author=Ed Tait |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/soccer/worlds-best-cant-beat-canada-258585901.html |newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date=May 9, 2014}}</ref> In June 2015, Winnipeg was one of six Canadian cities that hosted the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|FIFA Women's World Cup]]. The first four matches of [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Group D|Group D]]\u2014between the United States, [[Australia women's national soccer team|Australia]], [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]] and [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigeria]]\u2014were contested at Investors Group Field, followed by three matches from various other groups.<ref>{{cite news |author = Ed Tait |title = Winnipeg to host FIFA Women's World Cup |newspaper = [[Winnipeg Free Press]] |date =5 May 2012 |url = http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/soccer/Winnipeg-to-host-FIFA-Womens-World-Cup-150207165.html | accessdate = 2012-05-04}}</ref> Due to [[FIFA]]'s policy regarding commercial sponsorship of stadium names, the Investors Group Field was referred to as \"Winnipeg Stadium\" during the World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/destination/cities/city=18908/index.html |title=FIFA Women's World Cup Canada 2015\u2122 Destination: Winnipeg |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, IG Field became the home of [[Valour FC]] in the [[Canadian Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/winnipeg-soccer-franchise-fc-valour-1.4694586|title='Total excitement' as Canadian Premier League announces Valour FC, Winnipeg's new professional soccer team|last=|first=|date=June 6, 2018|work=Canadian Premier League|access-date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''2015 FIFA Women's World Cup'''\n{{Clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:left; width:85%;\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Time ([[Central Daylight Time|CDT]])\n!Team #1\n!Result\n!Team #2\n!Round\n!Attendance\n|