{"title_page": "Shrek the Halls", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Shrek the Halls\n| image                = Shrek the Halls poster.jpg\n| caption              = DVD cover\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = ''[[Shrek!]]''<br>by [[William Steig]]\n| writer               = [[Gary Trousdale]]<br />Sean Bishop<br />Theresa Pettengill<br />Bill Riling\n| director             = [[Gary Trousdale]]\n| starring             = [[Mike Myers]]<br />[[Eddie Murphy]]<br />[[Cameron Diaz]]<br />[[Antonio Banderas]]<br />[[Conrad Vernon]]<br />[[Cody Cameron]]<br />[[Aron Warner]]<br />[[Christopher Knights]]<br />[[Marissa Jaret Winokur]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[Harry Gregson-Williams]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Gina Shay]]<br />[[Teresa Cheng]]<br />[[Aron Warner]]\n| editor               = \n| cinematography       = \n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = [[DreamWorks Animation]]<br />[[Pacific Data Images]]\n| distributor          = [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]]\n| network              = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| first_aired          = {{Film date|TV=y|2007|11|28}}\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| budget               = \n}}\n'''''Shrek the Halls''''' is an American [[thankgiving]] [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[comedy film|comedy]] [[television special]] that premiered on the American television network [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on Wednesday, gucci mane in 2006. The thirty minute [[Christmas special]] was directed by [[Gary Trousdale]] and produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]]. [[Mike Myers]], [[Eddie Murphy]], [[Cameron Diaz]] and [[Antonio Banderas]] reprised their roles from the feature films. This Christmas special takes place between ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' and ''[[Shrek Forever After]]''. As with the other ''Shrek'' animations, this television special was based on the 1990 children's book ''[[no no square]]'' by [[William Steig]].\n\n== Plot ==\n[[Shrek (character)|Shrek]] ([[Mike Myers]])  is quietly living in the swamp with his family when the Christmas season arrives.  Under [[Donkey (Shrek)|Donkey]] ([[Eddie Murphy]])'s urging, Shrek reluctantly promises [[Princess Fiona]] ([[Cameron Diaz]]) a special Christmas surprise.  Shrek goes to the local bookstore in Far, Far Away to try to find a present for Fiona, but since he does not know what Christmas is all about, the shopkeeper ([[Marissa Jaret Winokur]]) gives Shrek a copy of ''Christmas For Village Idiots'', a step by step guide to celebrating the holiday. Shrek proceeds to follow the book's advice by decorating the house and getting a tree so he can spend a quiet Christmas Eve with his family, but Donkey brings the entire \"family\" to the swamp, spoiling Shrek's plans.\n\nAs Shrek tries to recite \"[[The Night Before Christmas|A Visit from St. Nicholas]]\", Gingy ([[Conrad Vernon]]), Donkey, and [[Puss in Boots (Shrek)|Puss in Boots]] ([[Antonio Banderas]]) interrupt and each tell their own Christmas story. Donkey tells of a Christmas parade passing by the swamp and licking an enormous waffle Santa, and absentmindedly starts licking Shrek's foot. Puss' version of the Santa Claus story ends with playing with the tassel on Santa's hat, while in reality he is playing with a bauble.\n\nGingy tells a horrifying story about how his girlfriend Suzy was eaten by Santa Claus. Donkey calls it ridiculous, and finds Shrek's ''Christmas for Village Idiots'' book. A fight breaks out over the book and Shrek's supper is destroyed. Shrek finally loses his temper and kicks his friends out of his house.\n\nWith their Christmas spirit ruined, Fiona is upset at Shrek's behavior and leaves with the ogre triplets. She catches up to their friends and explains to Donkey what Shrek had wanted for Christmas.\n\nShrek, remorseful at what he's done, catches up with the group and apologizes for his behavior. He then tells everyone this is also his first Christmas, since ogres don't celebrate anything. They return to the swamp and Shrek tells his own version of \"The Night Before Christmas\", featuring himself as Ogre Claus. Soon they hear bells and go outside to see Santa and his reindeer, although Gingy is still afraid of Santa Claus and runs back inside in fear. The special ends with Santa using his magic to put ogre ears on the moon.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mike Myers]] as [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]]\n* [[Eddie Murphy]] as [[Donkey (Shrek)|Donkey]]\n* [[Cameron Diaz]] as [[Princess Fiona]]\n* [[Antonio Banderas]] as [[Puss in Boots (Shrek)|Puss in Boots]]\n* [[Conrad Vernon]] as [[Gingerbread Man (Shrek)|Gingy]]\n* [[Cody Cameron]] as [[Pinocchio (Shrek)|Pinocchio]] and [[Three Little Pigs (Shrek)|The Three Little Pigs]]\n* [[Aron Warner]] as [[Big Bad Wolf (Shrek)|Big Bad Wolf]]\n* [[Christopher Knights]] as [[Three Blind Mice (Shrek)|Three Blind Mice]]\n* [[Frank Welker]] as [[Dragon (Shrek)|Dragon]] and [[List of Shrek characters#Dronkeys|Dronkeys]]\n* Miles Christopher Bakshi, Nina Zoe Bakshi, and Dante James Hauser as [[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus, & Felicia|Farkle, Fergus, & Felicia]]\n* [[Marissa Jaret Winokur]] as Bookstore Clerk\n* [[Gary Trousdale]] as Santa\n\n==Production==\n''Shrek the Halls'' was produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]], concretely, at the [[Pacific Data Images|PDI/DreamWorks]] studio. Gary Trousdale directed the special during the pre production, but he was later replaced by Mark Baldo. The film was produced by [[Teresa Cheng]], Gina Shay and [[Aron Warner]] and was screenplayed by Bill Riling, Theresa Cullen, Gary Trousdale and Sean Bishop.\n\n==Release==\n\n===Broadcast===\n''Shrek the Halls'' premiered on the American television network [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on November 28, 2007, in which they hold the exclusive domestic rights to the special until 2023.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shrek the Halls Airs November 28 on ABC|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=38878|accessdate=April 13, 2012|newspaper=ComingSoon.net|date=October 29, 2007|author=ABC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dreamworksanimation.com/2007AR/pdf/DWA_07AR.pdf | title=2007 Annual Report | website=DreamWorks Animation SKG | date=March 17, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928232607/http://www.dreamworksanimation.com/2007AR/pdf/DWA_07AR.pdf | archive-date=September 28, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref> In the United Kingdom, it premiered on December 24, 2007, on [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Shrek The Halls \u2013 the loveable green ogre comes to the smaller screen in his first Christmas special|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/12_december/07/shrek.shtml|accessdate=April 13, 2012|publisher=BBC|date=December 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nThe rating info is courtesy of ''Your Entertainment Now''<ref>{{cite web|last=Calabria |first=Rosario T. |url=http://entertainmentnow.wordpress.com/2007/11/29/broadcast-tv-ratings-for-wednesday-november-28-2007/ |title=Broadcast TV Ratings for Wednesday, November 28, 2007 \u00ab Your Entertainment Now |publisher=Entertainmentnow.wordpress.com |date=November 29, 2007 |accessdate=June 18, 2010}}</ref> and ''ABC Medianet''.<ref>[http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/progcal/dispDNR.aspx?id=120407_06 ABC Medianet<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It was repeated on BBC Three on December 23, 2011, along with ''Shrek: Once Upon a Time'' and ''Shrek''.\n\n====United States Nielsen ratings====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! #\n! Air Date\n! Rating\n! Share\n! Rating/Share<br />(18-49)\n! Viewers<br />(millions)\n! Rank<br />(timeslot)\n! Rank<br />(night)\n! Rank<br />(week)\n|-\n| '''1'''\n| November 28, 2007\n| 11.0\n| 17\n| 7.2/20\n| 21.06\n| 1\n| 1\n| 3\n|-\n| '''2'''\n| December 11, 2007\n| 5.7\n| 9\n| 3.4/9\n| 9.97\n| 3\n| 6\n| 21\n|-\n| '''3'''\n| December 1, 2008\n| 6.2\n| 10\n| 3.3/9\n| 11.17\n| 1\n| 3\n| 19\n|-\n| '''4'''\n| December 22, 2008\n| 3.7\n| 6\n| 1.8/6\n| 6.51\n| TBA\n| TBA\n| TBA\n|-\n| '''5'''\n| November 30, 2009\n| TBA\n| TBA\n| 3.2/8\n| 10.01\n| TBA\n| TBA\n| TBA\n|-\n| '''6'''\n| December 9, 2009\n| TBA\n| TBA\n| 2.6/8\n| 8.53\n| TBA\n| TBA\n| TBA\n|}\n\n====United Kingdom Figures====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Airing\n! Viewers<br />(millions)\n|-\n| '''December 24, 2007'''\n| 7.9<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewingsummary/weekreports.cfm?report=weeklyterrestrial&RequestTimeout=500 |title=BARB |publisher=BARB |date=June 6, 2010 |accessdate=June 18, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''December 24, 2008'''\n| 6.92*<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing/weekly-top-30 |title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes |publisher=Barb.co.uk |date=June 6, 2010 |accessdate=June 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318052904/http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing/weekly-top-30 |archivedate=March 18, 2013 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n<nowiki>* 6.32 million (BBC One viewers) + 0.60 million (BBC Three viewers) = 6.92. Both shown at the same time.</nowiki>\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Shrek the Halls'' was released on DVD in the United States on November 4, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=P. Vargo|first=Jason|title=Shrek the Halls DVD Review|url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/926/926518p1.html|accessdate=April 13, 2012|newspaper=IGN|date=November 3, 2008}}</ref> It was originally available by itself, or in a bundle pack with ''Shrek the Third''. It was released on iTunes on November 2, 2008. The special was released on Blu-ray and DVD on October 30, 2012, as part of compilation titled ''Dreamworks Holiday Classics''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dreamworks Holiday Classics: Merry Madagascar / Shrek The Halls / Dragons: Gift Of The Night Fury (Blu-ray + DVD) (Widescreen)|url=http://www.walmart.com/ip/21578976|publisher=Wallmart|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dreamworks Holiday Classics Blu-ray|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Dreamworks-Holiday-Classics-Blu-ray/52781/|publisher=Blu-ray.com|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref> It was re released on DVD on October 1, 2013 along with ''[[Merry Madagascar]]'', ''[[Kung Fu Panda Holiday]]'', ''[[Dragons: Gift of the Night Fury]]'', and ''[[The Croods]]''.  DreamWorks Holiday Classics, available on Amazon, features Donkey's Caroling Christmas-tacular and does not feature ''Shrek the Halls''.\n\n==Music==\nThe score of the special was composed by [[Harry Gregson-Williams]]. The special, like the films, also features the following [[Pop culture]] and [[Christmas]] songs:<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bonanno|first1=Luke|title=DreamWorks Holiday Classics Blu-ray + DVD Review|url=http://www.dvdizzy.com/dreamworksholidayclassics.html|publisher=DVDizzy.com|accessdate=March 7, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111091212/http://www.dvdizzy.com/dreamworksholidayclassics.html|archivedate=November 12, 2012|date=November 7, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* \"[[Summer Breeze (song)|Summer Breeze]]\"\n* \"[[Jingle Bells]]\" (sung by Eddie Murphy)\n* \"[[Here We Come A-wassailing]]\" (sung by [[I'm from Barcelona]])\n* \"[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|Because We Can]]\"\n* \"[[Jin-go-lo-ba|Jingo (Gin Go La Ba)]]\"\n* \"[[Ride of the Valkyries]]\"\n* \"[[The Twelve Days of Christmas (song)|The Twelve Days of Christmas]]\"\n* \"[[Santa Claus is Comin' to Town]]\"\n* \"[[O Fortuna]]\"\n* \"[[Christmas Wrapping]]\"\n* \"[[Gonna Make You Sweat (Everybody Dance Now)]]\"\n* \"[[Don't Stop Believin']]\"\n* \"[[Hello Ma Baby]]\"\n* \"[[Hallelujah Chorus]]\"\n* \"[[Deck the Halls]]\"\n* \"The Stars Shine in the Sky Tonight\"\n\n==ICE!==\nIn July 2011, as part of a strategic partnership between DreamWorks Animation and Gaylord Hotels, ''Shrek the Halls'' was presented as the theme of the ICE! exhibit at Gaylord's hotels in [[Gaylord Texan|Texas]] and [[Gaylord Palms|Florida]]. In this presentation, the plot of the film is told through a series of ice sculptures that visitors walk past.<ref>{{cite news|title=THIS CHRISTMAS, 'SHREK THE HALLS' AND GET 'MERRY MADAGASCAR' AT GAYLORD HOTELS|url=http://www.gaylordhotels.com/media-room/press-releases/2011/2011-07-19-dreamworks-christmas.html?intcmp=gh-pl=cnav-cid=CDW|accessdate=April 13, 2012|newspaper=Gaylord Hotels|date=July 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.dreamworksanimation.com/tv/shrek/}}\n* {{IMDb title|title=Shrek the Halls|id=0897387}}\n\n{{Shrek}}\n{{DreamWorks animated films}}\n{{Gary Trousdale}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2007 television specials]]\n[[Category:Shrek media]]\n[[Category:2000s American television specials]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Animation animated short films]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company television specials]]\n[[Category:Christmas television specials]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Gary Trousdale]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Gary Trousdale]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Shrek the Halls\n| image                = Shrek the Halls poster.jpg\n| caption              = DVD cover\n| genre                = \n| creator              = \n| based_on             = ''[[Shrek!]]''<br>by [[William Steig]]\n| writer               = [[Gary Trousdale]]<br />Sean Bishop<br />Theresa Pettengill<br />Bill Riling\n| director             = [[Gary Trousdale]]\n| starring             = [[Mike Myers]]<br />[[Eddie Murphy]]<br />[[Cameron Diaz]]<br />[[An